        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:106:"Q&amp;A Interview: Vaden Todd Lewis - A Toadies Concert Preview (Sunday, November 15, 2015 at Double Door)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:111:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/2015/11/interview-vaden-todd-lewis-toadies-preview-double-door-4508/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:120:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/2015/11/interview-vaden-todd-lewis-toadies-preview-double-door-4508/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 13 Nov 2015 13:41:51 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/?p=4508";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16351:"Headed to town for a stripped down set Sunday night at Double Door, I spoke with Toadies frontman Vaden Todd Lewis about restructuring Toadies hits on the new album <em>Heretics</em>, the influence of Willie Nelson on their annual "Dia De Los Toadies" festival, navigating murky major label waters and much more... <!--more-->

Vaden Todd Lewis and the Toadies spent much of 2014 looking back at the twenty years following their 1994 breakthrough, debut album <em>Rubberneck</em>, celebrating the anniversary with a special reissue of the album and a tour that featured a full performance of it.

Following the success of their Dia De Los Toadies festival - held annually in their home state of Texas since 2008 - shaking things up on record, and on tour, the way they do on stage at home seemed like a natural progression.

One of the hallmarks of that event, which the Toadies personally curate, is what frontman Vaden Todd Lewis calls the band's "chill" set, a set that often involves taking Toadies songs down to their bare bones, reworking them, adding different instrumentation, and ultimately reinventing familiar songs in a more acoustic based manner.

As that unique set evolved over the course of eight years onstage, the band decided to try and harness that vibe in the studio which wound up resulting in the sixth Toadies studio effort <em>Heretics</em>, released this past September by Texas based independent label Kirtland Records.

Touring for <em>Heretics</em>, the band will be performing their new take on a number of familiar Toadies hits in a more acoustic setting throughout a series of smaller, more intimate venues, allowing the storytelling of songwriter and vocalist Vaden Todd Lewis to drown out the guitar for the first time on a full, national tour.

Headed to town Sunday night for a stripped down Toadies set at Double Door, I spoke with Vaden Todd Lewis about the challenge of changing up songs fans expect to hear a certain way, the influence of the state of Texas on the new <em>Heretics</em> album, the mindset that empowered the band's 1994 breakthrough <em>Rubberneck</em>, catering directly to fans in the internet age and much more.  A lightly edited transcript of that phone conversation follows below...

<strong>Q.  You guys have been on tour at home in Texas for the last week or so before expanding it a bit more next week... How has the reaction been to the new songs and the new takes on the old songs so far?</strong>

<a title="Click HERE to visit the official Toadies website..." href="http://thetoadies.com/" target="_blank"><em>Vaden Todd Lewis</em></a>:  Very good.  It's been a blast.  I wasn't really sure with this whole new, weird thing we're doing -  I was just not really sure how people would react to it.  Especially getting down into the country, in Texas, people are reacting and responding really well.  I was pleasantly surprised a great deal.

<strong>Q.  You've picked some pretty interesting venues for this tour - the dance halls in Texas and, even here in Chicago, the Double Door which is a pretty intimate venue.  What was your mindset when it came to putting this tour together?</strong>

VTL:  We were wanting to make it just more intimate and make it kind of a chill event.  We wanted it to be very clear from the jump that this was not a big, loud rock show.  I want to make sure that everybody's having a good time... But I want to make sure that nobody bought a ticket thinking they were gonna rock balls.  So we tried to scale it down and make it intimate and cool and chill.  We'll be playing a lot of venues that are seated.

These dance halls are really cool.  We played the oldest and the second oldest dance halls in Texas last week.  It's so cool.  I've never been to these places that are out in the country.  They're just great people and it's a great experience to be able to go in there and play.  Gruene Hall - which I believe is the oldest dance hall in Texas.  Luckenbach.  Schroeder Hall.  The Dosey Doe.  Just cool old honky tonks [and] they're thriving!  It's just crazy.  Luckenbach and Schroeder, they're way, way... It's a long ways to anything!  They're not convenient so they're there for a reason.  It's really cool.

But I've always loved playing the Double Door.  I just love that place.  It's got a good vibe and a creepy downstairs dressing room hell.  It's just awesome!  I love it.

<strong>Q.  The most striking thing upon initially listening to <em>Heretics</em> is obviously the new interpretations of Toadies songs: specifically different instrumentation and arrangements.  For example, you added mandolin and keyboards to a track like "Tyler" and completely turned it upside down.  What's the creative process like for you guys when it comes to changing up songs that fans kind of expect to hear a certain way and making them work on an album like<em> Heretics</em>?</strong>

VTL:  It was a big challenge.  This whole thing started at Dia De Los <a title="Click HERE to visit the official Toadies website..." href="http://thetoadies.com/" target="_blank">Toadies</a>.  We just did the eighth one last month.  So it's been eight years.  Around the second year, we decided we would add a "chill" set the first night and make it two nights from one.  So we stripped it down and the first year that we did it it was acoustic guitars and we just kind of had fun with it.

The next year we expanded it a little bit more where Clark [Vogeler] plays keyboards a little bit.  Then it just evolved into this way different thing.  I guess it was a year and a half ago that we were thinking, "What if we did this in a controlled environment and made a record?  That would be pretty cool - just do it where we could just go crazy with it."  So that's what happened and that's what we wound up doing.

But as far as how to change the songs, the bottom line ethic for me is... I had read somewhere when I was a kid, one of my rock heroes - who I cannot think of right now - said that a good song is a good song regardless of what you play it on:  if it's on an acoustic guitar or piano or whatever.  So when we started taking these songs apart, I thought, "Well, that's a scary proposition because if I think these songs are good, then they should stand up."  So we just started running with it that way:  How can we play these completely differently but make it something different that shines a new light on what the song is?  So that's what we've done.

<strong>Q.  You mentioned your Dia De Los Toadies festival.  Can you speak to what that's become now over the course of eight years?  I'm especially intrigued by the fact that it was born almost as homage to Willie Nelson's Fourth of July picnics in Austin, right?</strong>

VTL:  Totally, yeah.  It started in probably ['08].  We got together to do a couple of St. Patrick's Day and radio things.  And we've done a million of those.  I mean a million.  And they're fun because you get to play... But you don't get to play as long as you want and you don't get to pick the bands you play with.  If you're lucky, there's bands you want to see... But often times not.  You're just kind of on the bill.  And that's what you signed up for in those types of situations.  It is what it is.

So we were thinking, "What if we did something crazy and did our own festival and promoted it ourselves and picked our own bands and modeled it after Willie's picnic and just made it a thing?"  And the label and management thought that was a good idea!  So they jumped on it.
<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" title="Toadies 2015" alt="Toadies 2015" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/files/2015/11/Toadies-Promo-2015-e1447437219369.jpg" width="400" height="280" /></p>
<strong>Q.  It would seem that the state of Texas is all over <em>Heretics</em> - it was born out of your more laid back sets at Dia De Los Toadies, features Black Joe Lewis's horn section and guest spots from Willie Nelson's harmonica player Mickey Raphael.  It was also released on Kirtland Records.  The state of Texas, almost without fail, unlike so many others, seems to really have an impact on the musicians and the music that comes out of it.  What kind of an effect does the state of Texas itself have for you now as a musician or has it had for you over the years?</strong>

VTL:  Jeez, that's hard to say because I'm in it.

I don't know... I've always been a big fan of ZZ Top and that kind of bluesy, shuffly sound.  It's kind of in the air here.

When I was a pre-teen and teenager, I was just into heavy metal.  Anything heavy metal - the heavier the better.  After a while, by my late teens, I started getting kind of burnt out on it and wanted a change, to hear something different.  The first thing I jumped over to was ZZ Top and The Cure - almost at the same time.  These were both things that my friends don't listen to! And that was just a springboard.

I went from there to Talking Heads and Pixies and all that stuff but still, at the root of it, is that bluesy, shuffly sound that kind of just informs the stuff I write.

<strong>Q.  One of the things I've always enjoyed about your songwriting is your ability to tell a story.  And it's something I kind of equate with so many different Texas musicians: The Reverend Horton Heat, The Old 97's, ZZ Top, Willie Nelson, all of the old country stuff.  All of those guys tell stories.  Is that idea of telling a story something that's important to you or something that you equate with a good song?</strong>

VTL:  Oh yeah.  Definitely.  I grew up on the horror classics.  Early on, I was reading Edgar Allan Poe and that freaked me out when I was a little kid.  Then I got a little older and it was Stephen King and stuff like that.  The weirder the better.

I've got very few songs that I've done that I would consider not being a story.  I love it.  I like taking somebody on a little journey.  To me, the whole idea of music is to kind of get you out of your surroundings and put you somewhere else for a little while.  I've always just loved being spirited away and I try to do that for people.

<strong>Q.  A big part of the <a title="Click HERE to visit the official Toadies website..." href="http://thetoadies.com/" target="_blank">Toadies</a> story would seem to be timing:  you guys got your start in the early nineties as alternative and grunge music started to hit and made different sounds more palatable on the radio for the first time in a long time. The Toadies didn't sound like the grunge rock out of Seattle and a radio listener then was just as likely to hear anything from Jane's Addiction or Tori Amos to R.E.M. and The Cure alongside the Toadies on the radio dial.  That period didn't last very long but, starting out, did it make it easier to make an album like <em>Rubberneck, </em>and release it in 1994, without worrying about what was "cool" or what was "marketable?"</strong>

VTL:  Well, this is gonna sound pretentious as hell but I didn't even think about that, about what was marketable.

Honestly, when we were doing <em>Rubberneck</em>, I just thought, "I have conned these guys into the biggest f---ing con that I've ever pulled off!  And they're paying us all this money to go in and record this record.  And then they have to put us on tour because... they have to!  So we'll get to see the States a little bit and then we'll go home!  And then ha ha, the joke's on you!"

That was my thinking process doing this record: "I'm gonna do exactly the record that I want to do."  Then it turned into a thing, fortunately, which was great.  But I've tried to keep that ethic going forward.  It really works for me just to get in there and not worry about what's going on outside the studio and just stay in the pocket as it were.

<strong>Q.  Once it became time to begin work on the second album, that era of uniqueness on the radio and on album was, essentially, already gone, which led to some of the issues you guys had with your label (Interscope) upon trying to get your sophomore effort <em>Feeler</em> released, initially, in 1998, before the label <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feeler_%28Toadies_album%29" target="_blank">shelved it</a> (it was eventually released in 2010).  Since then, you've kind of gone out of your way to avoid major labels, releasing the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burden_Brothers" target="_blank">Burden Brothers</a> material the way you did via the web early on.  Now the Toadies are partnered with a local Texas label (Kirtland) that was founded by musicians and would certainly seem to be a bit more artist friendly.  Looking back, it would seem to me that you were way ahead of the curve with the way you started carrying your business and catering directly to your audience.  Do you feel like that kind of prepared you a bit for reuniting the Toadies in 2006 in a much different music industry landscape than what the band left after breaking up in 2001?
</strong>

VTL:  In hindsight, sure.  The boring story of that is that I started writing, like I do when I'm home, and it didn't sound like The Burden Brothers, it sounded like the Toadies.  So that's what kind of inspired that getting back together.

But, yeah, in hindsight, I guess it did just make it easier to just do what we wanted to do.  We learned so much going through the major label wringer and we continually try to watch our steps going forward.  But that makes a lot of sense, yeah.

<strong>Q.  It can obviously be a bit of a double-edged sword for a musician but what's your take on the web as an artist who has no other choice but to utilize it now.  Has it helped you to kind of eschew the major labels to some extent?</strong>

VTL:  Oh yeah.  Once the internet became, well, a thing, I realized pretty quickly that... Remember back in the day when like Metallica was suing whoever, Napster?  Or people individually?  I just thought, "That's not gonna make anybody happy.  Anybody!"  Even the bands... you're not gonna do to well out of this!  I just didn't get it. My thought was, "Well, it's the internet.  Now everything's free."  That's just the way it works.

So that's just kind of the ethic I've had.  You just have to find different ways to do what you do and make a living at it.  Fortunately, we have a good team that helps us navigate that.
<em><strong>- Jim Ryan (<a title="Follow me on Twitter @RadioJimRyan" href="https://twitter.com/radioJimRyan" target="_blank">@RadioJimRyan</a>)</strong></em>

