<!--more-->

When it comes to making music, one of the biggest challenges to Steve Marker, as both a producer and guitarist, is how to ensure the music sounds different.

In their work over the course of the past twenty years, Garbage has consistently managed that largely by refusing to look back, setting themselves apart from many of their nineties alternative peers in the process.

So it's rare to catch the band on a tour like the one that brings them to a sold out Riviera Saturday night - one which celebrates the occasion of their twentieth anniversary via a full performance of the fifteen songs which encompass their self-titled, 1995 debut album.

Despite the brief shot of nostalgia, new music is on the horizon with the possibility of their sixth studio album coming as soon as this May.  A journey into the world of self-release with their 2012 effort <em>Not Your Kind of People</em> seems to have empowered the band, freeing them up to create on their own terms, a liberating experience which continues to influence them during the latest Garbage recording sessions.

I spoke with producer and Garbage guitarist Steve Marker over the phone about the strange process of looking back at their debut album twenty years after its release, what allows that album to remain fresh and relevant, its legacy, the importance, in a continually changing music landscape, of being different and the surreal experience of walking into a near riot outside the Aragon Ballroom on the infamous December night of the live pairing of Sonic Youth with Public Enemy.  What follows below is an unedited transcript of that conversation...

<strong>Q.  You guys strike me very much as a band which typically prefers to move forward.  What’s it like looking back now at the twenty years following your 1995 debut album?</strong>

<a title="Click HERE to visit the official Garbage website..." href="https://www.garbage.com/" target="_blank"><em>Steve Marker</em></a>:  It is a little odd. Over the years, I've always been a lot more interested in the next thing - what the next song's gonna be or what our next album's gonna be like. Sometimes when you put an album out and you go on the road - sometimes it was up for two years that we'd tour - you're definitely ready to move on.

So you're right: Looking back, in a somewhat nostaglic way, is a little odd... but also really fun. Because a lot of the stuff that we're playing, we've never played before. When we had to go back and figure out "What the hell did I do in the studio there, twenty years ago, to get that sound? I have no idea." It was pretty late at night if you know what I'm saying!

So it's been an interesting exercise. And a lot of fun. We're kind of trying to be pretty true to how the first record sounded - probably more than we ever did in the past. It's just been kind of interesting. Because the technology's all different and the equipment's all different. I think it's gonna be pretty cool... I hope!

<strong>Q.  In looking back at the album, and re-learning songs you've never performed live, was there anything during that process that surprised you?</strong>

Marker:  Yeah. Some of the guitar parts that I did, I had a lot of trouble figuring out how they went. Like any kid would do, sitting down and trying to figure something out off the radio, I'd have to sit down with the tape playing a section over and over going, "How did I do that?" So that was surprising.

I don't feel like I ever got sick of our earlier stuff.  But some of the stuff we've never played and some of the stuff we've played well over a thousand times in concert.  I never got tired of them but maybe you get complacent with them. I guess there's a bit of trying to remember what the original spirit was behind making it in the first place and using that in the sort of new interpretation that we're trying to come up with for this tour.

That was interesting. Instead of just being like, "Well, I remember what I did last summer on the festival circuit when we played 'Stupid Girl,' so I'll just do that again" it was more like going back thinking, "Where we were we at mentally when we did this?" And equipment wise. And sonically. And we'd kind of start from there when we started rehearsing these songs.

I guess you forget how sometimes I actually did think that some of what we did was kind of damn cool, you know? It turned out really well. And maybe you forget that a little bit. We're all sort of self-deprecating a little bit and maybe don't give ourselves enough credit sometimes. So it's kind of fun to sit down and turn that up and think, "You know, that's a pretty good album!"

<strong>Q.  The idea of performing an album in its entirety to celebrate an anniversary is a popular concept at the moment, especially amongst your nineties alternative peers. But, to me, the difference with this album is the way it has endured – it still sounds pretty fresh.  It doesn’t sound dated. What do you attribute that to?</strong>

Marker:  We made it in Madison, Wisconsin and there was barely the internet. There was MTV. And there was [Chicago radio station] XRT. And the Madison stations. But we weren't like in the middle of lower Manhattan or in Hollywood listening to what everybody else was doing and trying to keep up with that. We were sort of bumbling along and doing our own thing. We weren't too worried about fitting in I guess. So maybe that was good.

There's some stuff we did that, maybe, was difficult for the times. We were using the guitars and the drum machines and the sampling, and starting to use Pro Tools, and trying to do it with pop melodies... And, for whatever reason, that combination worked out for us. I don't think that we were that worried about what the latest drum sound was. And we didn't have the latest samplers for the time.

I guess the answer is, I have no idea! But I'm grateful that you say that. Sometimes you hear something and go, "Oh that's that 1986 snare drum sound." And it is dated immediately. We, luckily, through partial incompetence and ignorance avoided that a little bit in some way.

<strong>Q.  What do you feel like the legacy of the debut <a title="Click HERE to visit the official Garbage website..." href="https://www.garbage.com/" target="_blank">Garbage</a> album is now or what do you hope it will become?</strong>

Marker:  I guess its legacy is that twenty years later we're able to go out and play it for people and they'll still show up and be interested in it. I guess that's kind of a legacy - and one that we're really grateful for.

It's not the "I Have a Dream" speech or something of that significance. But it played a part in people's lives I think. That's what they tell us now. And it meant something to them - it still does in a lot of cases. And I think we have to honor that and be grateful for it. I know I am.

[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="400"]<img title="Garbage - Photo by Joseph Cultice" alt="Garbage - Photo by Joseph Cultice" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/files/2015/10/Garbage-Photo-by-Joseph-Cultice-e1444875164128.jpeg" width="400" height="300" /> Photo by Joseph Cultice[/caption]

<strong>Q.  You guys self-released your last album in 2012, a first for Garbage.  It’s easier to self-release than ever before but, at the same time, I would imagine it also brings about a lot more concerns for the band too. What was that self-release experience like for you guys and what kind of an impact do you think it will have on the band moving forward?</strong>

Marker:  I think it's been incredibly liberating. Basically, everybody says this - because radio has changed and the culture has changed - and bands like us are not gonna be, necessarily, on a major label. And that's just how it is. And it's been really good for us.

We don't have anybody telling us to do anything we don't want to do. In the past, we had to make videos and had to compromise. It's always your money you're spending but [label] people say, "You really have to work with this video director today! Or this remixer. And you're gonna pay for it but you really have to do it or..." And we don't get that anymore.

It's really great. If there's someone we want to work with - a photographer say, whatever it is, or we want to tour somewhere - we can kind of just say we want to do that and try to make it happen. It's kind of cutting out the middle man. We sell less records but we make more on each record. So in a way it's really good for us.

We never really enjoyed being directed that much. I think we were a little bit older and a little bit more savvy when we started out than maybe some people. So we didn't take kindly to being told what to do by labels and that's kind of led to a lot of our problems on the business end. We ended up going through a few different labels and things like that. And it's nice to just be clear of that. We can succeed or fail on our own terms and it's a much healthier place to be mentally.

<strong>Q.  There’s been some new songs here and there over the last few years, especially with the Record Store Day releases, but are you guys working on more new music?</strong>

Marker:  We sure are. We spent about a year and a half of me coming back and forth to L.A. We've been recording in [producer and Garbage drummer] Butch Vig's basement and various studios. We have a new album, that I don't know the title to yet, but it's gonna be out probably in May. It's pretty much almost ready to be mixed.

This twentieth anniversary thing is almost like a little interlude before we get to next year. We're hoping to be touring a lot next year playing completely different stuff with a new album, marching forward.

<strong>Q.  When it comes to making new <a title="Click HERE to visit the official Garbage website..." href="https://www.garbage.com/" target="_blank">Garbage</a> music in 2015, in a music industry landscape that has moved further and further from the idea of the traditional, full album release in the twenty years since your debut, what is Garbage's current approach to new music:  Do you still think in terms of the album, and making an artistic statement in that manner, or has that become less important to you guys?</strong>

Marker:  I think the album is, in an old fashioned sense, back. More like the way things were when I was a kid probably. Which I love. I listened to both sides of vinyl when I was growing up more than single songs on the radio.

Back in the day, even when we were making the early albums, there were still people that would put money into what we were doing and were really hoping that we would come up with the next number one single. And it's kind of hard to get that out of your mind, even if you say you don't care about that. They still would be really, really happy to see that number one single. And, now, we're not gonna have a number one single. Because we're not Rihanna - don't want to be. So, cool. That's great.

In a way, that lifts a lot off your shoulders and kind of frees you up to do stuff. Like on this [new] album, there's one or two songs that are really long - they're not single length. They're more like seven or eight minutes. And it doesn't matter. If that's what we feel like works on the album, that's what we'll do.

<strong>Q.  I’ve heard you say that one of the most important things to you as a producer is to create something that sounds different. In today’s music culture, there’s not a lot breaking through right now that sounds different. How important is that idea of being different to you guys when it comes to getting together and working on new Garbage music?</strong>

Marker:  I think it's more of a concern than ever. To me, the way recording has gone - and we do it too - but everybody can kind of do anything on their laptop now. There's a lot of really standard building blocks that people use to make songs. I listen to electronic music... but there's a lot of people using all the same instruments and the same beats and the same drum machines and I think there's a lot of boring things going on because of that.

Sonically, I don't hear a lot of interesting things. Like, in the seventies, if you had Roxy Music playing a pop song, it was gonna sound pretty damn weird. Or if [Brian] Eno is doing something on a production. Things like that. You'd even hear stuff on "Top 40" radio that would sound pretty weird. That's the kind of thing that I love.

I'd hate to think that things get kind of samey. We're maybe not blazing the trails of new sonic frontiers... but we're trying to. We're trying to make things sound interesting to us. And different. To me, that's one of the most important things when I hear something on the radio or on a record.

<strong>Q.  Over the course of the last twenty years, Garbage has played an awful lot in Chicago – whether it’s your own tours, radio station gigs, opening for acts like U2, etc.  I saw an interview where you told a story about seeing a Public Enemy/Sonic Youth show here and it made me curious if there are any particularly fond memories of Chicago that stick out for you in terms of performing with Garbage in Chicago…</strong>

Marker:  Before Garbage even, we were all in bands that played at the Cubby Bear. I was like a roadie for Butch and [Garbage multi-instrumentalist] Duke [Erikson] and their band and they would play the Cubby Bear almost once a month. Avalon was another one. And up and down Clark Street.

But, man... <a title="More on the 1990 riot outside the Aragon at the Chicago Reader..." href="http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/fighting-the-power/Content?oid=876972" target="_blank">that riot</a> at the Public Enemy/<a title="More on the 1990 riot at the official Sonic Youth website..." href="http://www.sonicyouth.com/mustang/cc/122990.html" target="_blank">Sonic Youth</a> show. Somebody [must have] called something in to the police and just about every Chicago cop was outside when we came out. It was like, they started this riot. There was nothing going on in the crowd [during the concert]. It was weird... rap was like really dangerous then. Like all these indie kids form Evanston were gonna come down and mix with these rap guys from the south side? This is gonna be like West Side Story or something?

And there was like 100 cop cars with their lights on outside of the show. And we kind of had to run to get out of there. The Aragon I think?
But that <a title="Read the Chicago Tribune's 1990 review of the Sonic Youth/Public Enemy concert at the Aragon Ballroom..." href="http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-01-01/features/9101010058_1_public-enemy-sonic-youth-flavor-flav" target="_blank">combination of music</a> was obviously something that struck me real hard - the beats and that sort of in your face sound combined with the dreamy guitars. It's kind of obvious but it was such a powerful idea at the time.

So that probably sticks out for me the most of a Chicago show.

<em><strong>- Jim Ryan (<a title="Follow me on Twitter @RadioJimRyan" href="https://twitter.com/radioJimRyan" target="_blank">@RadioJimRyan</a>)</strong></em>

