        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:132:"Q&amp;A Interview With Robert Randolph and John Medeski (Concert Preview: The Word - Monday, October 12, 2015 At Concord Music Hall)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:132:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/2015/10/interview-john-medeski-the-word-robert-randolph-concord-music-hall-interview4467/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:141:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/2015/10/interview-john-medeski-the-word-robert-randolph-concord-music-hall-interview4467/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 09 Oct 2015 18:18:01 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/?p=4467";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15166:"Headed to town for a show Monday night at Concord Music Hall, I spoke with keyboardist John Medeski and pedal steel guitarist Robert Randolph about what makes their partnership with the North Mississippi Allstars in the band The Word special, their work together on the second Word album <em>Soul Food </em>and<em> </em>why it's important for them to create uplifting music...

<!--more-->

The conversation between John Medeski and Robert Randolph has a natural flow.  Nothing seems forced, everything seems fun and, above all else, the absolute love of music, and everything it's capable of, is clear.  That spirit sums up the pair's latest collaboration, <em>Soul Food</em>, with North Mississippi Allstars Luther Dickinson, Cody Dickinson and Chris Chew as The Word.

Born out of a mutual love of gospel music - specifically the "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacred_Steel_(musical_tradition)" target="_blank">sacred steel</a>" tradition and its value of the steel guitar - between Medeski and the Allstars, the group's self-titled debut plucked Randolph from relative obscurity circa 2001, exposed him to a recording studio for the first time and, ultimately, made possible the secular success he'd come to enjoy fronting his family band in the years to follow.

As is often the case when it comes to a "supergroup," hectic touring schedules for each member of The Word - Randolph with his own band, Medeski in Medeski Martin &amp; Wood, Luther Dickinson as a member of the Black Crowes and North Mississippi Allstars tours alongside outings backing John Hiatt - made it difficult to get together and record.

But it never stopped the group from performing together periodically.  And as both Randolph and Medeski are quick to point out, The Word's best moments on record are born out of live performance.  So even with fourteen years between their only two studio albums, the group's potent mix of rock, soul, gospel, blues, jazz and more remains a potent one.

I spoke over the phone with John Medeski and Robert Randolph about the unique relationship that continues to make The Word special to them, the idea of incorporating spirituality in their music and why it's important to give the world positive, uplifting music in the year 2015.  What follows below is a lightly edited transcript of that phone conversation...

<strong>Q.  Well, your second album was released in May and it marks the group's first since 2001. With all of the touring and recording that each of you do with your own respective projects, I would imagine it has to be extremely difficult to get everyone together to write and record. What made this the right time for The Word to work on a new album?</strong>

<em>Robert Randolph</em>:  It all just really worked out.  We had talked about it over the past ten years or so.  We had some days off and we talked about it. We got together just to kind of see what energy we had or to see if things would sort of fall back into place.  So we got into Brooklyn for two or three days in a studio and there was just a lot of magic happening, a lot of music - a lot of great creative energy.

So we started to build on that and here we are today.

<strong>Q.  Let’s talk about the new album.  I've heard the debut album in 2001 came together in a matter of days and it sounds like this one might have followed a similar path.  You recorded <em>Soul Food</em> in both Brooklyn and Memphis - how long did you wind up working on the album and what kind of an effect did each studio have on the finished album?</strong>

<em>John Medeski</em>: We did a couple of days in Brooklyn and then a couple of days in Memphis.

<em>Randolph</em>:  I think it's just a sound and a vibe.  For us, I think it really doesn't matter which studio we're in.  We could be in a garage playing loud.

When you mix all these different sounds and influences together, it becomes the base of doing some gospel/instrumental, sort of sacred steel influenced stuff.  Once you sort of base it all off of that, then we just kind of... go.

It's a mixture of gospel and rock with some really bluesy influences.  Then we'll all just start playing.  John will start playing something on the organ or the piano.  Cody [Dickinson] will have so many ideas.  And Luther [Dickinson] will have ideas.  I'm gonna have some ideas.  It'll just keep going and going and going.  We kind of actually have to stop ourselves all the time.  Because the energy and the creative magic is something that just keeps happening!

<em>Medeski</em>:  Yeah, in Memphis we had to shut it down... because we were getting too much material! <em>(laughs)</em> We were like, "Alright, we gotta stop and just deal with what we've got and work on it."  It's really true.

Robert and I live up in the New York area and the [North Mississippi] Allstars all live down in North Mississippi or Memphis.  So it was just a natural choice to do a little recording in both places.

<strong>Q.  The debut album featured more traditional gospel songs than the new one does. Was that a logical direction to head this time around, to explore more of the collective, original sounds that you guys are capable of creating together?</strong>

<em>Randolph</em>:  I think what happens when we get together is the less thinking we could do, the more we could get done.  It's kind of one of those things.  If we all just play and then talk briefly about what we're gonna do, we'll get more done.  More talking just kind of confuses things.

It's funny because a lot of times us musicians can kind of get in our own way.  We've all been blessed with the ability to make magical music.  And the more we kind of hush up and play and compose, the more we'll get done.  I think that's really what makes this band sort of just... work.  And come together.

<em>Medeski</em>: Yes.

<em>Randolph</em>:  Most times, we're actually kind of clueless where we're gonna start and where we're gonna end.  We just sit down and we play and go, "Ok.  I guess we're done!" <em>(laughs)</em>

<em>Medeski</em>:  If you really listen, the music has a life of its own.  And it's clear what needs to happen next.  And if it's not really clear, we look at each other and somebody can give a look or a nod and send it in a certain direction.

