        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:121:"Q&amp;A Interview With Albert Hammond, Jr. of The Strokes (Concert Preview: Tuesday, September 15, 2015 at Bottom Lounge)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:161:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/2015/09/qa-interview-with-albert-hammond-jr-of-the-strokes-concert-preview-tuesday-september-15-2015-at-bottom-lounge/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:170:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/2015/09/qa-interview-with-albert-hammond-jr-of-the-strokes-concert-preview-tuesday-september-15-2015-at-bottom-lounge/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 15 Sep 2015 15:42:10 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://www.chicagonow.com/chicago-at-night/?p=4452";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15547:"Headed to town Tuesday night for a show at Bottom Lounge in support of his third solo album <em>Momentary Masters</em>, I spoke with Strokes rhythm guitarist Albert Hammond, Jr. about the path to sobriety that helped shape his latest record, learning to have fun again and much more... <!--more-->

When it came time to start thinking about his third solo album - the sessions with longtime producer Gus Oberg that encompassed what eventually became <em>Momentary Masters - </em>Strokes rhythm guitarist Albert Hammond, Jr. was very much influenced by astronomer Carl Sagan's book <em>Pale Blue Dot</em>.

The journey out of rehab, which eventually led him back to the studio, featured stops along the way to ponder subjects like the loss of innocence and, more to the point, whether it was possible to experience music in the way most children do upon falling in love with it for the first time at a young age - to have fun with it.

In talking with Hammond, it's clear just how much he values his current band and just how much his comfort level with them has grown.  Together, they all crafted <i>Momentary Masters</i> in the studio and as they continue to work together on the road, bond deepening, it's anyone's guess where the music they'll continue to make will go.  But it's clear Hammond wants to keep making it.  With this band.  Because it's fun again.

Headed to Bottom Lounge for a set Tuesday night with his band, I spoke with Albert Hammond, Jr. over the phone last month about crafting his third solo album <i>Momentary Masters</i> (and what sets it apart from his work with The Strokes), the idea of new beginnings, having fun and much more.

A lightly edited transcript of our conversation follows below...

<span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;">Q.  This will be your first time back in Chicago performing in support of your new solo album Momentary Masters since Lollapalooza.  Whether it’s the festival circuit or the smaller clubs, how have these dates with your new band gone so far?</span>

<i><a href="http://alberthammondjr.com/" target="_blank">Albert Hammond, Jr</a>.</i>:  I’m excited for that.  Actually, I was rehearsing for Lollapalooza and we rehearsed at Music Garage so I walked by [Bottom Lounge].

We’ve only really done Primavera right before the album came out and then Lollapalooza and The Tonight Show and a few radio things.

So I’m looking forward to actually playing our own show and doing our own kind of setlists.

<b>Q.  This album, while clearly a rock album, also kind of seems to have more of a rhythm to it than some of your previous solo work – you can really kind of move to it, dance to it.  Was writing with that idea of rhythm in mind a concerted effort or is that just kind of how this batch of songs came out?</b>

AHJ: I guess a little bit of both.  I felt like I was missing songs in the set and there were certain vibes from bands I had been listening to – Wire, Wipers, Misfits – that I wanted when I played live.  So I did my own interpretation of that.

I feel like we could play this whole album and it definitely has a great energy to it on the record and especially live.

<b>Q.  There’s a very unique style to your solo recordings, especially on the new album. There seems to be a lot more guitar too.  When it comes to crafting these solo songs now, how is that process different than when you’re working with the Strokes?</b>

