 L7, Jimmy Cliff, The Airborne Toxic Event, Tommy Stinson, Tenacious D, Snoop Dogg, Modest Mouse, Damian Marley, The Prodigy and more… <!--more-->

The biggest story, maybe of the entire weekend, was just how shockingly dry it was in Douglas Park to start the third and final day of Riot Fest 2015 on Chicago’s west side.

Standing water receded and while there were still isolated, easily avoidable areas of mud, Sunday might have featured the best festival-going conditions of any of Riot Fest’s four years now as an outdoor festival in a Chicago city park.

The cleanup process is no doubt already in progress but Sunday was the type of day that has the possibility to save organizers not just significant money, as repair costs begin to tabulate, but also headaches.

And, especially given Riot Fest’s more recently embattled status, it’s worth noting, once again, that Riot Fest featured the most easy-going, well behaved concertgoers of any festival to take place in Chicago this year.

Chicago has become one of the most festival populated cities in North America featuring major, outdoor, three day festivals like Lollapalooza, Pitchfork, North Coast, Riot Fest and more.

One of those festivals has become almost laughable in its lack of response to continually escalating and embarrassing audience antics (and it’s not Riot Fest).  It’s a shame so many people at the local level ignore that fact and assume the worst of Riot Fest simply because they’re scared of the word “Riot.”  The growing, negative public perception of Riot Fest in that regard is misguided and utterly mind-boggling.

If Saturday’s slate of live music performances was geared toward legends like Merle Haggard, Iggy Pop and more, Sunday’s story was decidedly that of the success of rap and hip-hop with performances by De La Soul, Cypress Hill, Yelawolf, Snoop Dogg and more.

And it's a story which has no doubt rankled longtime fans of a festival that cut it’s teeth booking – and reuniting – primarily punk rock acts since it’s humble beginnings at small clubs throughout the city like Double Door and Congress Theater since 2005. But Riot Fest's eclectic array of musical bookings has become one of its most successful elements, especially over the past four years.

One of the best, positive, most energetic sets of the entire weekend came over the course of forty-five minutes early Sunday afternoon courtesy of De La Soul.  “This isn’t gonna be your typical hip-hop show” said the group early on.

Hip-hop is often at its best when backed by a live band.  But De La Soul proved that theory very wrong in a set dominated by some of the most impressive audience participation of the entire weekend.

“It’s sunny, be happy!” said the group moments before “Me Myself and I” rang out across Douglas Park.  It was a triumphant set in every possible way.

Hum also performed early Sunday, a rare opportunity to catch the pride of Champaign, Illinois in the live setting as they’ve played sporadically at best since about 2000 with only a handful of Chicago dates in the past fifteen years.

Still featuring all four members from their most successful era, the alternative rock group hit upon a forty-five minute set that veered at times from mere alternative to something more resembling pyschedelia infused metal.

“I’d Like Your Hair Long” from their underrated 1995 debut <i>You’d Prefer an Astronaut</i> came early and, in between checks of the Packers/Bears score, their biggest hit, “Stars,” came late.

But it was “I Hate it Too” that both closed and stole the set. It began with a sparse arrangement featuring only the vocals of Matt Talbott and the guitar of Tim Lash before the rest of the band kicked in midway through.  Hum was at it’s most animated during the passionate performance and it stood out as one of Sunday’s best.

Cypress Hill delivered a surprisingly strong set Sunday as well.  And it was impressive just how good B-Real still sounds, delivering his trademark high pitched vocals throughout a forty-five minute set.

As always the group spit lovingly about marijuana during cuts like “Hits From the Bong” and got the crowd moving with a slew of hits including “How I Could Just Kill a Man” early and “Insane in the Brain” late.

Riot Fest 2015 also featured reunion sets by two of the better all female, nineties alternative acts with Babes In Toyland delivering on Saturday and L7 kicking things up a notch Sunday.

As was the case throughout the first two days, sound was an issue again Sunday.  At times the between song banter of Hum’s Matt Talbott was almost indecipherable and fans clearly wanted it louder at the beginning of L7’s set.

Featuring a reunion of their most enduring and successful lineup (guitarist/vocalist Donita Sparks, guitarist/vocalist Suzi Gardner, bassist/vocalist Jennifer Finch and drummer Demetra Plakas), the group hit upon elements from most of their career, going back to 1990 for the opening “Deathwish,” immediately following with one of their biggest hits in “Andres” from their 1994 high watermark <i>Hungry for Stink</i>.  “Suck it, Trump!” they yelled upon launching into “One More Thing,” one of the few politicized moments all weekend.

But just as Saturday belonged to a legend in Merle Haggard, Sunday did as well in the form of 67 year old reggae icon Jimmy Cliff.  Displaying the  energy of a performer half his age, Cliff was without a doubt one of the weekend’s most animated stars.

“You Can Get it if you Really Want” came early in a set dominated by an incredibly tight eight piece backing band that featured a horn section, multiple keyboard and guitar players and more.

The best covers of the weekend also belonged to Cliff who hit on a gorgeous version of Cat Stevens’ “Wild World” before strapping on a guitar himself for his 1993 cover of Johnny Nash’s “I Can See Clearly Now.”  Given the weather, the latter was incredibly appropriate as the sun began to set on Douglas Park.

“This song is from the movie that brought reggae to the whole world!” declared the Rock and Roll Hall of Famer triumphantly as the band launched into the outstanding “The Harder They Come” from the 1972 film of the same name.  Cliff’s dancing during the song belied a youthful exuberance and, paired with the song’s uplifting lyrics, it was one of the more positive moments to take place all weekend.

Assuming Snoop Dogg would hit the stage late, as he generally does (spoiler alert: he did), it was off to see Replacements/Guns N’ Roses bassist Tommy Stinson and his new band featuring fellow GNR member Frank Ferrer on drums alongside Steve Selvidge of The Hold Steady on guitar, bassist Cat Popper (Ryan Adams’ Cardinals) and keyboardist Tony Kieraldo

Despite a sparse crowd, the group ran through a terrific forty-five minute set that hit upon cuts like “Breathing Room” from an upcoming, new Stinson solo release.

Clad in a t-shirt featuring a spray-painted “R” on it (perhaps a nod to fellow Replacement Paul Westerberg’s <a href="http://www.paulwesterberg.com/tag/shirt-watch/" target="_blank">series of shirts</a> to close out the recent run of Replacements reunion dates) Stinson ended a strong set with “Never Aim to Please” and “Friday Night (Is Killing Me)” from his excellent 1993 post-Replacements project Bash &amp; Pop.

Assuming Snoop would be late was a sound strategy though it may have led to a disappointing set for fans waiting to hear him perform his 1993 album <i>Doggystyle</i> in its entirety.  While a strong set, it was by no means a full performance of that album, veering instead to a more hits oriented one with performances of covers like Dr. Dre’s “Nuthin' but a ‘G’ Thang,” and House of Pain’s “Jump Around” as well as hits like “Drop it Like it’s Hot,” and “Young, Wild and Free.”

Sometimes Snoop performs backed by a band and other times it’s merely him and an MC.  Of all the material in the Snoop Dogg catalog, <i>Doggystyle</i>, in particular, given it’s heavy George Clinton influence, deserved the full band treatment… But Snoop didn’t bother performing most of the album anyway.  At one point, he seemed to blame festival organizers for his delay though, again, it’s worth noting that he’s seldom on time.

That said, he did hit on choice cuts from the seminal G-Funk album like “Gin and Juice,” a remixed “Lodi Dodi,” “Who Am I? (What’s My Name?)” and “Tha Shiznit” and the crowd ate it up.

<em>- </em><strong><em>Jim Ryan</em> (</strong><a title="Click here to follow me on Twitter @RadioJimRyan" href="https://twitter.com/radioJimRyan" target="_blank"><strong>@RadioJimRyan</strong></a><strong>)</strong>

